node.text:
“You will be challenged during the next four years, but you can do it,” said Academy Superintendent Lt. Gen. Richard Clark. “Take one bite at a time. The first step is completing basic cadet training, and you have already demonstrated you have what it takes to succeed by getting here. I stood where you stand almost 40 years ago and I’m so glad I stuck it out.”

The global COVID-19 pandemic may be on the decline, but the Air Force Academy took no chances when more than 1,100 young men and women reported to the school for basic cadet training, June 24.

The trainees arrived between 7 a.m.-noon, were given facemasks, and immediately tested for the coronavirus.

Check out more on this story at www.usafa.edu.

node.text: Today, cadets march in a Founders Day Parade honoring the legacy of #youracademy. Together, we stand on the foundation built by those who came before us, striving to strengthen that foundation for those who come after us, reinforcing our bonds with a culture of dignity and respect. Being part of the Long Blue Line means being part of something bigger than ourselves, collectively building and bolstering the bridge to the future @usairforce  and  @spaceforcedod. The more we treat each other with dignity and respect, and ensure that this is a fundamental part of our culture, the higher we’ll rise together.

node.text:
As we honor Black History Month, I’d like to take a moment to share with you one of my favorite stories about Rosa Parks. I share this in hopes that when we think of civil rights exemplars such as Rosa Parks, the Tuskegee Airmen, Dr. Martin Luther King, and the many other pioneers of integration and racial equality, that we also reflect on ourselves. How can we better ourselves and understand that together we have an opportunity to become not only better Air and Space Forces, but a nation that champions diversity and inclusion?

node.text:
You know what day it is, #FirstieFriday! Who better to start off with than our very own Cadet Wing Commander, C1C Michael Herrington!

From Flowery Branch, Georgia, Michael first learned about the Academy while participating in Air Force JROTC and Civil Air Patrol in high school.

He is majoring in Computer Science with a minor in Spanish and is a member of the Cadet Honor Guard and Space Operations Squadron. Michael hopes to commission into the Space Force as a Space Operations Officer. 

Among his most memorable experiences at the Academy are Recognition and working as BCT cadre.

His advice to prospective and current cadets - don't give up! 

"Lean on your friends and classmates; it's ok to ask for help! Remember the end-goal; it's easy to get caught up in the day-to-day and forget why you're doing what you're doing (especially as a 4-degree)!"

#YourAcademy

Yesterday we broke ground on a multimillion-dollar construction project to build a cyber center that will bolster the Air Force and Space Force’s cyber war fighting capabilities. 

When complete, the 33,000 square-foot Madera Cyber Innovation Center will feature state-of-the-art cyber-tech classrooms, labs, research and design spaces for cadets to explore advanced computer and cyber science concepts, and facilitate collaboration with industry, academia and local partnerships.

“To me, the most rewarding part of this research program experience has been seeing all of the new technologies that are currently being used, or will eventually be used by the US military ... [the experience] has opened my eyes to a whole new side of what it takes to be a well-rounded officer in the Air Force.”

During Cadet Summer Research Programs, cadets are able to correlate lessons they have learned in the classroom to real-world practices. This summer, C1Cs Caleb Carnes and Qadry Brown were immersed in the science of providing living and training spaces for the military in an expeditionary environment, also known as bare base beddown planning. They gained skills with BEAR kits and Airfield Pavement Evaluation (APE) tools, techniques, and procedures used by engineers to construct airfields and extended capabilities in austere locations.

Visit usafa.edu to read more.

Gates at the Air Force Academy will re-open to the public Monday, August 2nd. 

While we are excited to welcome the general public back to #youracademy, the health and safety of our cadets, staff, service members and families remain our top priority. 

All visitors must comply with our current mask mandate, which requires everyone to wear a mask while indoors regardless of vaccination status. 

Many of your favorite locations will be open, including the Visitor Center (weekdays only). However, the Cadet Chapel remains closed for renovations and the Planetarium is closed due to parking lot construction which also impacts access to Arnold Hall. 

Check out goairforcefalcons.com for information about attending your favorite @af_falcons  athletic events.
